{
  "texts": [
    "IntroductionSensor-based Human Activity Recognition (HAR) is a well-known research topic extensively studied in pervasive computing [14].",
    "The HAR task involves determining the most likely activity performed by a subject through the intelligent analysis of sensor data collected from one or multiple devices (e.g., wearables, environmental, radio-based).",
    "The adopted sensing technologies influence the granularity at which activities can be recognized.",
    "For instance, using inertial sensors in mobile/wearable devices makes it possible to detect physical activities like running, walking, and standing still.",
    "On the other hand, environmental sensors are particularly useful for recognizing high-level Activities of Daily Living (ADLs) like cooking, taking medicines, or watering plants in smart-home environments, also considering that subjects at home are less inclined to carry or wear devices all the time.Among the many applications of sensor-based ADL recognition in the areas of energy management, safety, well-being, and healthcare, the long-term monitoring of the ADLs performed by elderly subjects in their homes gained significant importance [41]."
  ]
}